                                                                                                                <comments>
                            <comment id="14461469" author="phkim" created="Thu, 25 Aug 2005 17:13:27 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;This issue has been fixed, but is not closed yet, since currently this works only when the subclass and superclass exist in the same groovy file.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;For more informations, see&lt;br/&gt;
&lt;a href=&quot;http://cvs.groovy.codehaus.org/changelog/groovy/groovy/groovy-core?cs=MAIN:phk:20050825220835&quot; class=&quot;external-link&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow noopener&quot;&gt;http://cvs.groovy.codehaus.org/changelog/groovy/groovy/groovy-core?cs=MAIN:phk:20050825220835&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
</comment>
                            <comment id="14461490" author="blackdrag" created="Thu, 25 Aug 2005 17:37:05 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;accessing protected attributes of a superclass is one thing, making them practically public another thing. Example:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt; c = new EmptyRange(null)&lt;br/&gt;
 asset c.EMPTY_LIST==[]&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;this  should fail because of an illegal property access. The field EMPTY_LIST is protected in EmptyRange and as the script above is neither a subclass of EmptyRange nor is it in the same package, the attribute should not be accessible. &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;You may remember I mailed you the idea how to solve this&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="14461830" author="blackdrag" created="Fri, 10 Feb 2006 09:43:34 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;this is another thing for the new MOP, so I assign this to John&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="14462380" author="blackdrag" created="Tue, 28 Nov 2006 06:32:53 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;sometimes people can be so blind... Stupid me didn&apos;t saw that SubClass is not extending SuperClass. Of course it is not possible to access x then! &lt;/p&gt;</comment>
